reviews.review_text:
Playing Extravaganza! Thanx Tiger Rose, David, & Andrew.  This is a great audience recording.  In fact it is audience recordings like these that generally make me prefer them to boards.
This was my fifth show.  I managed to catch 3 of the first four of this tour, missing Charlottesville, which was closest to my home.  I drove a motorcycle to the show from North Carolina, meeting some friends who went ahead.  Serendipity hits as we simultaneously pull into parking stalls next to each other.  I remember cops on horses and an otherwise strong police presence.  
The first set is unique and very well played.  I love the Crazy Fingers.    Even as a newbie I could tell these were the types of shows that kept bringing you back for more.
The second set starts off with a nice Shakedown>brief Playing jam.  It is too bad the reprise never came nor did any of the Playing Jams go for long or far.  Great Sailor/Saint and just like that Drums.  Not really much of a space but a building jam into NFA that is quite good.  Nice read on Stella, particularly the outro jam.  First Touch of Grey sent me and my folks home happy.  I am playing Playing through Day Job on my radio show this week.  Peace

WHERE DID THE FIRST SET GO? WE STARTED THIS TOUR WITH A BANG.DRIVING INTO THE PARKING LOT A TAD LATE WE OPENED A BIG BAG OF CAPS AND STEMS AND PASSED THEM AROUND.WE KNEW WE HAD ALOT OF GROUND TO COVER THIS WEEK FROM HERE TO PORTLAND TO BOSTON TO NYC BUT WE ATE LOTS AND LOTS.WITH THE UNUSUAL PLAYIN' IN THE BAND TO START I THOUGHT WE MISSED THE FIRST SET BUT EVERYONE AROUND ASSURED ME I DID NOT,VERY STRANGE.THE SHOW WAS GREAT UP TO THE DRUMS AFTER THAT IT WAS AVERAGE AT BEST.BUT UP TO THAT POINT WE WERE LOST IN THE OZONE AGAIN.BUT GOOD THINGS WERE TO COME IN CUMBERLAND COUNTY BUT THAT IS ANOTHER REVIEW.

Mics sound like they are onstage This is a spectacular FOB!

Really digging fall 82 lately, the setlists were heavy on crazy fingers and playin.  This has some very unique combinations and have enjoyed it a few times in the past few weeks.

Peace

Reliving the Past While a student at F&M in 1982, my friends and I attended this show at the Cap Center.  A shout out to Doctor Bob for leaving a remnant on the Cap Center parking lot!

The Shakedown brought back some good memories, as did the first ever Touch of Gray as an encore.

I miss those days!

Excellent sounding Not sure how I missed this recording. Tiger Rose you captured the feel of being there again. 
We got the east coast break out of Crazy Fingers. Lucky to catch all of them in 82.

best recording of the early 80s thank you TIGER ROSE!!!'

check out the space > jam > NFA

might need to resole your brain after that one!
Amazing, pure and simple The first recording of touch of grey, stellar

primo show this is just a beautiful, intense, creative show with about the best FOB you'll ever hear -- sounds like you're down in about the 15th row. 

my first time backstage, and then back to the hotel 'hospitality suite' -- what an eye-opener (!)... thanks to my buddy, frank streeter, for that hook-up, and then getting us in backstage in portland two nights later. 

80-82 just about my fav era, and this show captures the grateful dead in peak form.

thanks Wow, great sounding recording....many thanks,  I remember when high quality 82 and 83s were tough to find -- not sure if the SBDs were circulated -- or maybe I was just out of the circle.  Playin - crazy to open ,,, a solid Shakedown and excellent sound -- I did not attend, did not discover Jerry G until 87..but did hit Landover in 87 and 88.  Enjoy - gotta love the archive and the effort put in by the tapers/transfer people,  Many Many thanks,,,,
